Extensions to Regression Model

Polynomial Regression

model:

simple case: \(x\) is one dimensional

\(\hat{y_i} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \beta_2 x_i^2 + ... + \beta_d x_i^d\)

predictors:

  • \(X = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & x_{1} & x_{1}^2 & x_{1}^3 & \dots & x_{1}^d \\ 1 & x_{2} & x_{2}^2 & x_{2}^3 & \dots & x_{2}^d \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 1 & x_{i} & x_{i}^2 & x_{i}^3 & \dots & x_{i}^d \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 1 & x_{N} & x_{N}^2 & x_{N}^3 & \dots & x_{N}^d \end{bmatrix}\)

Residual Diagnostics

Assumptions of linear regression

  • Linear relationship
  • Normality
  • Homogeneous variance
  • Independent observations

How to check?

  • Residual plot
  • Q-Q plot
  • Also need to check residuals for outliers, influencial points, high leverage points

Magnitude or even sign of the coefficient could be wrong if did not carefully check for residuals

What to do if residuals do not match assumptions?

  • Transformation of X and/or Y
  • Weighted Least Square Model
  • Non-independece: time series model

Transformations

set.seed(2)
N = 300
x1 = rnorm(N, 0, 1)
x2 = rpois(N, 3)
x2 = ifelse(x2>0, x2, 1)
x3 = runif(N, 5,15)

# Ex1 Transform X
y = 0.3 + 0.6 * x1 + 2 * log(x2) + rnorm(N, 0, 0.5)

mod = lm(y ~ x1 + x2)
summary(mod)

Bias Variance Tradeoff

\(Y = f(X) + \text{noise}\)

\(E[(Y - \hat{f}(X))^2] = Bias(\hat{f}(X))^2 + Var(\hat{f}(X)) + \text{noise term}\)

\(Bias(\hat{f}(X)) = E[\hat{f}(X) - f(X)]\)

\(Var(\hat{f}(X)) = E[\hat{f}(X)^2] - E[\hat{f}(X)]^2\)

There is trade-off between bias & variance

  • Low Bias: linear model fit linear data
  • High Bias: linear model fit non-linear data
  • Low Variance: model little dependent on train data

  • High Variance: model highly dependent on train data

  • Low Bias: build complex model for complex data

  • Low Variance: Average your model

Chase for low bias and ignore high variance may cause overfitting problem

Overfitting

  • learning noise rather than data
  • fitting complex model on simple data
  • good performance on training set bad performance on testing set
  • usually large coefficients in regression model

remind LSE \(\hat{\beta} = (X^TX)^{-1}X^Ty\)

Control Overfitting

  • use more data
  • regularization
  • Subset Selection
  • dimensionality reduction

Interaction Terms

When to add interaction terms? - It is not good recommended to add all interaction terms into model (overfitting, computational complexity) - Come up hypothesis with domain knowledge & intuition, e.g.price sensitivity is different based on users income, thus add interaction of price * income - Test your hypothesis by adding interaction term into model and check for significance or do variable selection

Regression Splines

Examples Kids will grow about 2 inches and gain 4 pounds each year until puberty (usually between 8 and 13 for girls and 10 and 14 for boys). Girls often reach their full height around 15. Boys usually hit their adult height around age 17

Step Function:

\[C_i(x) = \begin{cases} x & x\leq c_i \\ 0 & x > c_i \end{cases} \]

Step Function Model:

\(\hat{y_i} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 C_1(x_i) + \beta_2 C_2(x_i) + ... + \beta_K C_K(x_i)\)

predictors:

  • \(X = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & C_1(x_{1}) & C_2(x_{1}) & C_3(x_{1}) & \dots & C_K(x_{1}) \\ 1 & C_1(x_{2}) & C_2(x_{2}) & C_3(x_{2}) & \dots & C_K(x_{2}) \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 1 & C_1(x_{i}) & C_2(x_{i}) & C_3(x_{i}) & \dots & C_K(x_{i}) \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 1 & C_1(x_{N}) & C_2(x_{N}) & C_3(x_{N}) & \dots & C_K(x_{N}) \end{bmatrix}\)

best \(\beta\)

Least square minimize MSE

Basic Function:

\(\hat{y_i} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 b_1(x_i) + \beta_2 b_2(x_i) + ... + \beta_K b_K(x_i)\)

so step function model and polynomial model are just special case of basic function.

Regression Splines

Like piecewise polynomial regression, but with constraints on knots(where coefficient changes).

\(\hat{y_i} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \beta_2 x_i^2 + ... + \beta_d x_i^d + \beta_{d+1}(x_i - \xi_1)_{+}^m + ... + \beta_{d+K} (x_i - \xi_K)_{+}^m\)

In order to achieve continuity, we need to add this feature(truncated power basis)

\[(x - \xi)_{+}^m = \begin{cases} 0 & x\leq \xi \\ (x - \xi)^m & x > \xi \end{cases} \]

predictors:

  • \(X = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & x_{1} & x_{1}^2 & x_{1}^3 & \dots & (x_1 - \xi_1)_{+}^m & \dots & (x_1 - \xi_K)_{+}^m \\ 1 & x_{2} & x_{2}^2 & x_{2}^3 & \dots & (x_2 - \xi_1)_{+}^m & \dots & (x_2 - \xi_K)_{+}^m \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \dots & \vdots \\ 1 & x_{i} & x_{i}^2 & x_{i}^3 & \dots & (x_i - \xi_1)_{+}^m & \dots & (x_i - \xi_K)_{+}^m \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \dots & \vdots \\ 1 & x_{N} & x_{N}^2 & x_{N}^3 & \dots & (x_N - \xi_1)_{+}^m & \dots & (x_N - \xi_K)_{+}^m \end{bmatrix}\)

best \(\beta\)

Least square minimize MSE

Usually, we choose polynomial degree to be 3, known as cubic spline, basically human cannot recognize discontinuity at degree of 3.
